headline: JB Hunt Reports Robust Q2 Results; Street Says Buy
summary:
Arkansas-based transportation and logistics firm JB Hunt Transport Services (JBHT) has reported solid second-quarter 2021 financial results. The company mainly operates large semi-trailer trucks and offers transportation services across Mexico, Canada and the continental U.S.



Earnings per share (EPS) increased 41% year-over-year to $1.61, surpassing the Street’s estimates of $1.55. Total operating revenue surged 36% year-over-year to $2.91 billion, beating expectations of $2.7 billion.



Intermodal segment’s revenue climbed 21% to $1.29 billion; revenue of Dedicated Contract Services segment was up 17% at $621 million; Integrated Capacity Solutions segment’s revenue doubled to $607 million; revenue of Final Mile Services segment rose 52% to $212 million; and Truckload segment’s revenue surged 70% to $184 million.



Meanwhile, JB Hunt’s shares closed 3.2% lower at $159.68 on Monday. (See JB Hunt stock chart on TipRanks)



Last week, Citigroup analyst Christian Wetherbee reiterated a Buy rating on the stock and raised the price target from $197 to $205 (28.4% upside potential). In a research note to investors, the analyst said, “The rate outlook appears to reflect continued strength in spot rates coupled with progress through a robust contract bid season for the carriers.”



Overall, the stock has a Moderate Buy consensus based on 4 Buys and 5 Holds. The average JB Hunt Transport Services price target of $179.11 implies 12.2% upside potential. The company’s shares have gained 18.8% over the past year.



According to TipRanks’ Smart Score rating system, JB Hunt scores a 9 out of 10, suggesting that the stock is likely to outperform market averages.
